The solution () has an apparent singularity at
, but as it was noted in Ref. , the first two
terms in Eq. () describe a 5D de Sitter space.  The 5D
inflation rate is , and the surface
 corresponds to the de Sitter horizon.  This shows that the
space outside the monopole core inflates not only along the 4D
worldsheet, but also in one of the transverse directions, while two of
the extra dimensions remain compactified in a sphere.  This behavior
is reminiscent of the topological-inflation scenario , 
where inflation occurs in the cores of topological
defects in 4D.  There are, however, important differences.  First,
the defect core has a fixed radius and is not expanding in the radial
direction, and second, two of the extra dimensions remain
compactified, also at a fixed radius.

Although the 4D expansion rate  drops out of the asymptotic
solution, it is a meaningful parameter for the full spacetime.  With
our boundary conditions at , it gives the inflation rate in the
core of the monopole.  As we saw in the preceding section, the static
 solutions with  are singular.  As  is
increased, the singularity gets milder, and at a certain value of 
it disappears completely, resulting in a cigar geometry.  We interpret
the corresponding solution as the physical solution describing the
spacetime of a superheavy defect.  

Our conjecture is that for each , only one particular value of
 gives a nonsingular solution.  Of course, it is impossible to find
this precise value numerically, and therefore, all super-critical
numerical solutions that we considered eventually developed a
singularity.  The nature of the singularity is similar to that of a
static solution in Fig. , with  and .  
By adjusting the value of , we were able to shift the onset of the
singularity to larger and larger radii, so that the solution got
closer and closer to the asymptotic solutions
()-().  In the end, however,  invariably
started to diverge, at some point very close to the would-be de Sitter
horizon, .  We believe that our
results are very suggestive, but they do not, of course, constitute a
proof that all values of  except one yield singular solutions.  
It may be possible to provide a proof using the dynamical-systems
method employed in Ref. .

